FMSP, FMSP General
41.1 FMSP General
� General Information
The operation of a spark-ignition combustion engine is strongly linked on availability of a mixture with a speci?c
air/fuel ratio.
The theoretical ideal mixture for complete combustion is a mass ratio of 14.7:1 (relevant for gasoline fuel),
referred to as the stoichiometric ratio. In concrete terms this translates into a mass relationship of 14.7 kg of
air to burn 1 kg of fuel, while the corresponding volumetric ratio is roughly 9,500 litres of air for complete
combustion of 1 litre of fuel.
Figure 41.1.1: Ration between air and fuel mass
The basic fuel mass injection setpoint quantity (FMSP) is calculated out of the air mass ?ow via the stoichio-
metric factor in order to reach the theoretical mixture.
The Fuel Mass Setpoint Aggregate can support three different system versions:
a). Multiple port injection (injection into manifold)
In multi point injection systems to each cylinder is assigned a fuel injector, which injects the fuel directly ahead
of the cylinders intake valve:
Single injection capability
Homogeneous mixture distribution
Regulation of engine performance via throttle valve
b). Direct injection (injection into combustion chamber)
In direct injection systems, to each cylinder is assigned a fuel injector, which injects the fuel directly inside the
cylinder:
Improvement of fuel economy, reduction of NOx emissions and hydrocarbon emissions
Multiple injection capability
No fuel can precipitate on the intake manifold walls.
The study of the location/behaviour of this formation in the combustion chamber led to two com-
pletely different operating modes:
- Strati?ed operation
- Homogeneous operation
- Homogeneous - Strati?ed operation
c). Multiple port injection + direct injection
In multi point and direct injection systems, to each cylinder are assigned two fuel injectors, which injects the
fuel directly ahead of the cylinder?s intake valve and also inside the cylinder:
Improvement of fuel economy, reduction of NOx emissions and hydrocarbon emissions
Multiple injection capability

FMSP, FMSP General
The study of the location/behaviour of this formation in the combustion chamber led to two com-
pletely different operating modes:
- Homogeneous operation
- Strati?ed operation
- Homogeneous - Strati?ed operation
Fuel Mass Setpoint aggregate is mainly interfaced with the following aggregates:
Intake System (INSY)
Lamda coordination(LACO)
Combustion Modes Manager (CBMD)
Injection Realization(INJR).
Figure 41.1.2: FMSP - interface with other aggregates
Intake system is providing the predicted air mass value (MAF_STK_FG_PRED) which is used to determinate the
basic injection quantity.
Lamda coordination is providing the lamda controller (FAC_LAM_AD_OUT, MFF_ADD_LAM_AD_OUT) in?uence
used to correct the injected quantity in order to achieve the ideal mixture.
Combustion modes manager is the central coordination function that collects the inputs from different re-
questers (e.g. start, catalyst heating, scavenging) and provides the calculated combustion mode via IDX_CMB_
MOD_CUR. The combustion mode contains the injection system information (MPI mode, SDI mode or mixed
MPI/SDI mode), the operating mode information (homogeneous/homogeneous-strati?ed/ strati?ed) and also
the multiple injection split (e.g. IDX_CMB_MOD_CUR = NC_IDX_OPP_MPI_3_S_1 which means combustion mode
mixed operation (MPI/SDI), injection operating point (HOM/HOM/S), triple pulse)
Depending on the active combustion mode, FMSP is calculating the split up for multiple injection during start
and after-start phases.( FAC_MFF_MPL_INJ_ST, FAC_MFF_MPL_INJ_HOM)
Injection realization is consuming the fuel mass setpoint output (MFF_HOM_SP) in order to determine the
injection time.

FMSP, FMSP General
� Architecture Overview
Figure 41.1.3: FMSP - modules signal ?ow
41.1.1 Objectives of the aggregate
The goal of fuel mass setpoint aggregate is to calculate the following functionalities:
Basic fuel mass (including variable valve lift)
The basic injection functionality calculates the basic fuel amount considering the stoichiometric air/fuel ratio
of a reference fuel. It is the required fuel mass to run the engine at lamda = 1.
Correction during cold-start, warm-up and restart
The fuel mass at start and after start is map-based pre-controlled (no lamda control).
The cold post start correction is necessary to compensate the effect of building up wall ?lm after cold start.
Even the pre- and start injection fuel mass consider this effect by there calibration. The difference in the
calculation after start is now that the basic fuel mass is calculated out of the determined mass air ?ow.
For a warmed up engine a speci?c warm up correction have to be considered. The injected fuel mass has to
be increased because of the building up of the wall ?lm at start and after start, because of fuel condensation at
the cold combustion chamber wall (the fuel goes into the oil) and because of fuel droplets which go through
the engine without taking part at the combustion.
In order to improve restarts, a correction factor on the mass fuel ?ow during pre-injection and start injection is
calculated. The fuel mass at restart has to be decreased (values below zero) because of the already build up
wall ?lm from the last engine run. After several minutes this wall ?lm evaporates so that the restart correction
becomes neutral.

FMSP, FMSP General
Calculation of multiple injection via the MFF split up factors
The functionality provides the determination of the pulses of one injection cycle according to the selected
combustion mode. By instance, if the combustion mode is requesting double injection the functionality will
determine which percentage from the basic fuel amount will be dedicated to the ?rst pulse and the rest until
100% will be assigned to the second one. (i.e. 40% on the ?rst pulse, 60% on the second)
Fuel mass setpoint aggregate calculates the injected fuel quantities for all possible operating modes: homoge-
neous, homogeneous-strati?ed and strati?ed.
Figure 41.1.4: FMSP ? operating modes
Consideration of intake-bank and cylinder-individual corrections
This functionality provides an intake bank selective correction factor MFF_COR of the injected fuel mass de-
pending on the actual operating point (load, engine speed). This correction accounts for bank speci?c differ-
ences of the air charge.
Dynamic corrections (wall ?lm compensation, restart fuel feed)
To compensate the build-up / removal of the fuel ?lm in the intake ducts, the wall ?lm compensation function
provides an additive positive/negative mass fuel ?ow MFF_ADD_WF.
During fuel cut off phase, the manifold wall-?lm becomes cut down until it has completely disappeared. In order
to guarantee, after a cylinder shut-off, safe ?ring with fast torque build-up without mis?ring of the reactivation
cylinder, this must be supplied with an extra amount of fuel for the following reasons:
- increased charge due to lack of residual exhaust gas
- wall-?lm degradation during cylinder shut-off
Because of the different numbers of cut off cycles for the cylinders, the extra fuel amount is calculated individ-
ually for each cylinder.
Fuel quality adaptation
The purpose of fuel quality adaptation is to make sure that the engine runs without any dependency on fuel
quality. This aim is realized by an increasing or a decreasing of the injection time by a factor. For that the fuel
quality is recognized by the engine speed gradient at start.
The whole function is based on the analysis of the increase of the engine speed during the start. If a too
low engine speed gradient at start is detected the adaptation factor for the start fuel injection time will be
increased. Engine speed gradients being too high are leading to a decrease of the adaptation factor.

41.4.4 RUNTIME OPTIMIZATION
This chapter describes runtime optimization steps. First step is to reduce cylinder dependent calculations from
all cylinders to one cylinder, dependent on the engine speed. An additional step is to reduce bank dependent
calculations to the intake or exhaust bank, which is allocated to the related cylinder by NC_IN_REF and NC_
LAMB_REF.
For engine charge optimization a half segment calculation recurrence is introduced, which depends on an
engine speed threshold. Below this threshold MAF, MFF and TI calculation will be updated twice per segment
(half segment calculation). Because of that a higher engine dynamic can be realized especially for low engine
speeds.
De?nitions of the non calibratable constants to generate STATE_CLC_RED
NC_STATE_CLC_RED_SEG_HALF = 0x02H
NC_STATE_CLC_RED_SEG_1 = 0x04H
NC_STATE_CLC_RED_SEG_2 = 0x08H
NC_STATE_CLC_RED_SEG_4 = 0x10H
NC_STATE_CLC_RED_CLC_DEAC = 0x40H
NC_STATE_CLC_RED_ACT = 0x80H
NC_STATE_CLC_RED_MASK_1 = 0x1EH
NC_STATE_CLC_RED_MASK_2 = 0xC0H
Application hint:
ID_CTR_CYL_NR_CLC describe the cylinder number, which will be calculated exclusive on the segment with the
number SEG_NR, even if the runtime reduction is active. Therefore you have to specify the segment cylinder
relation here proper to your engine type.
Note that the related intake and exhaust banks will be calculated automatically by NC_IN_REF and NC_LAMB_
REF.
41.4.4.1 Check runtime optimization conditions
The switch to run time optimization is only possible at segment number 0. A switch to half segment calculation
is possible at each segment or half segment as long as ENSD enables half segment calculation (LV_SEG_HALF_
ENSD_ENA).

� General Information
In order to improve re starts, a correction factor on the mass fuel ?ow during pre injection and start injection
is calculated. This factor in or decreases the mass fuel ?ow.
If a valid value for the engine-off-time is available (LV_T_ES_NOT_PLAUS = 0) the factor is calculated dependent
on the engine condition at shut down (IP_FAC_REST) and the engine-off-time (IP_REST).
The engine condition at shut down is determined by the coolant temperature at shut down TCO_STOP and
the engine running time of the last driving cycle T_AST_STOP which are both stored in non volatile memory.
The engine-off time T_ES_H and the decision of validity LV_T_ES_NOT_PLAUS comes out AGGR ENSS. In case
of engine stalling detection (LV_STALL = 1) an additional correction factor is applied to the calculation of the
restart factor.
If no valid value for the engine-off-time is available the standard restart function detects the necessity of a
restart correction depending on T_AST_STOP and the difference between the actual TCO and TCO_STOP (max-
imal difference: C_TCO_DIF_MAX_REST).
The restart factor is determined by the map IP_FAC_STND_REST dependent on the actual coolant tempera-
ture TCO. In case of engine stalling detection (LV_STALL = 1) an additional correction factor is applied to the
calculation of the restart factor too.
The ?ag LV_REST indicates that a restart correction factor not equal to zero is applied to the mass fuel ?ow
calculation.
If the vehicle supports alternative fuel e.g. E85 (NC_AFU_CONF = 1) the interpolating tables are doubled i.e. two
sets of tables are supplied for gasoline and alternative fuel operation, respectively. The actual correction factor
depends on the alternative fuel content FAC_AFU_RATIO. Interpolation between gasoline and ?ex fuel oper-
ation is performed by the tranfer function IP_FAC_AFU_RATIO_REST since fuel properties cannot be lineraly
interpolated.

metric factor IP_MFF_FAC_AFU dependent on the alternative fuel ratio and the air mass per stroke.
It is the required fuel mass to run the engine at lambda 1.
For the air mass two different values (MAF_STK_FG_PRED/MAF_STK_FG_PRED_MPI) can be chosen dependent
on the combustion mode and its necessary prediction (DI or MPI). As soon as the engine is running MFF_BAS
is calculated. During start this is not required, but it inhibits a peak in the wall?lm compensation due to its
activation.

FMSP, Cold post start correction
The main output is ADD_MFF_CAST calculated based on the following main parameters: coolant temperature,
engine speed, manifold air pressure.
If the vehicle supports alternative fuel e.g. E85 (NC_AFU_CONF = 1) the interpolating tables are doubled i.e.
two sets of tables are supplied for gasoline and alternative fuel operation, respectively. The actual correction
factor depends on the alternative fuel content FAC_AFU_RATIO. Interpolation between gasoline and ?ex fuel
operation is performed by the transfer function IP_FAC_AFU_RATIO_CAST since fuel properties cannot be linear
interpolated.

41.8.3.1 Cycle counter for PUC operation
The counter CYC_PUC_CAST is calculating the number cycles in ?fuel cut off? operation mode. Each time when
?fuel cut off? phase is active (LV_PUC=1) the CYC_PUC_CAST is enabled.
Long PUC operation phases during the cold post start phase need to be taken into consideration (e.g. cold
start at the top of a mountain and driving downhill right after start). PUC operation has to be activated before
the cold post start correction is no longer active.

FMSP, Warm up correction
� General Information
This module calculates a fuel mass correction factor which have the purpose to optimized the emissions until
engine reach the optimum running temperature.
The factor calculation is based on the coolant temperature at start, engine speed, mass air ?ow parameters.
For warming up the engine the correction factor FAC_MFF_WUP is necessary in order to reach the lambda
set point. The injected fuel mass has to be increased because of fuel condensation at the cold combustion
chamber wall (the fuel goes into the oil) and because of fuel droplets which go through the engine without
taking part at the combustion.
If the vehicle supports alternative fuel e.g. E85 (NC_AFU_CONF = 1) the interpolating tables are doubled i.e. two
sets of tables are supplied for gasoline and alternative fuel operation, respectively.

41.9.2 Warm up correction factor calculations
41.9.2.1 Calculation of warm up enrichment factor (non alternative fuel system NC_AFU_CONF =
0)
The calculation of warm up factor depends on the engine speed and mass air ?ow base map (IP_FAC_MFF_
WUP) which is weighted by fuel quality adaptation (IP_FAC_FQ_WUP) and speci?c customer warm up (FAC_
MFF_WUP_CUS) factor.
If the last engine start was stop-start start a speci?c factor is also taken into consideration in order to reduce
the hot start rich mixture. (IP_FAC_MFF_WUP_HST).
The deactivation factor (max from IP_FAC_MFF_TCO_WUP and IP_FAC_MFF_TCO_MAF_INT_AST_WUP) which
assure the warm up factor fading out is dependent on mass air ?ow and coolant temperature.

ACTION_FMSP_CalcFacMffSplit(IN <PRM_IDX_CMB_MOD>, OUT <PRM_FAC_MFF_SPLIT [NC_NR_IV_PLS]>)
� General Information
This function calculates the injected fuel mass (bank-speci?c value). There are different stages distinguished:
0. Pre-injection
The pre injection function has a separate interface to the basic software.
As long as the pre injection function is active the basic software drives the injectors via this interface.
1. Mass fuel at start (pre-controlled)
In this state the fuel mass is pre-controlled via start maps. The fuel mass is still corrected due some start
corrections (depending from AMP, fuel quality, restart and external parameter)
2. Transient phase (linear gradient)
In this state a ramp over from the pre-controlled mass to the guided mass is done. The ramping starts at exit
start

rections
are considered (->MFF_SP_CLC). At the end with external and manual corrections the ?nal fuel mass will be
calculated.

culated MFF_SP_HOM[1] (calculated at start). MFF_AST is ramped down with the decrement MFF_LGRD_AST.

Afterwards MFF_SP_CLC[i] and MFF_AST are compared and the bigger value is selected for further calcula-
tions. MFF_AST(n) = MFF_AST(n1) MFF_LGRD_AST.

MFF_ADD_LAM_AD_OUT_FMSP =
MFF_ADD_LAM_AD_OUT_MPI + MFF_ADD_LAM_AD_OUT_HPDI

41.10.4.4 Calculation of MFF_SP_HOM
If MFF_AST is greater than MFF_SP_CLC the fuel mass for homogeneous injection mode is set to MFF_AST.
Otherwise it is set to MFF_SP_CLC (mass air ?ow guided). Further MFF_SP_HOM accounts for external correc-
tions. For test purposes the set point can be set manually. The fuel mass set point for the fuel pressure control
is set to the mean value of MFF_SP_HOM if the injection time is long enough (LV_TI_1/2/3_HOM_MIN = 0).

� General Information
MFF_SP_EFP_CTL and MFF_SP_MV are set to MFF_SP_HOM_MV. MFF_SP_EFP_CTL is used for the low pressure
electrical fuel pump control functionality.
MFF_SP_FUP_CTL is input for the high pressure fuel pressure (FUP) control functionality. This variable accounts
for the actual injection ef?ciency EFF_INJ_AV which considers cylinder shut-off. It is used for the balancing of
the fuel mass in the rail.
MFF_SP_FUP_SP is used for the fuel pressure set point FUP_SP calculation without considering cylinder shut-
off.

� General Information
This module calculates the fuel mass split up factor for the actual combustion mode. Based on the split factor

� Application Conditions

10MS activated if !LV_ST_END

FMSP, MFF split up for multiple injection at HOM mode (Appl. Inc.)
Basic values are de?ned in map IP_FAC_[cmb_mod]_[number of pulse].
Pulse with highest number is calculated ?rst.
Next pulse is 1 - (value(s) of previous pulses). For this last pulse is always calculated, not calibrated.
Maps have to be calibrated in a way that sum of all factors = 1.
For warm up (WUP) conditions it is possible to adjust split up factors depending on TCO.
Values are calibrated with IP_FAC_[cmb_mod]_[number of pulse]_WUP and fading dependent on TCO is done
with IP_RATIO_[cmb_mod]_WUP.
Another calculation is done to avoid reaching of TI_MIN.
The ACTION_INJR_ClcTiMin4 is called, this delivers TI_MIN of actual pulse.
To this value offset C_TI_MIN_HPDI_OFS is added. Together with C_TI_STND_SDI and FAC_FUP_RATIO_STND
an inverse behavior of injector characteristic is calculateded and delivers, divided with MFF_SP_HOM_MV, the
minimum split up factor to avoid TI_MIN.
This value is shown as FAC_MFF_MIN_HPDI [NC_NR_IV_PLS].
If this value is greater than calibrated value, split up factor is increased up to calibrated limitation IP_FAC_[cmb_
mod]_[number of pulse]_MAX.

41.12.3.1.1.2.5.3.2 Temperature correction factor for fuel mass split up in OPP_MPI_2_S mode
The temperature correction can be calculated in two different ways for the combustion modes which have
split up between MPI and DI:
1. If (NC_MFF_TEMP_WUP_HOT_SWI = 0) then we use two different temperature factors de?ned for "cold"
and "warm" conditions. Using the fading ratio de?ned from 0 to 1 we can fade between cold/warm temperature
levels
2. If (NC_MFF_TEMP_WUP_HOT_SWI = 1) then we use three different temperature factors de?ned for "cold",
"warm" and "overtemperature" conditions.
Using the fading ratio de?ned from 0 to 2 we can fade either between cold/warm or between warm/overtemperature
temperature levels.

41.12.3.1.1.2.5.5.2 Temperature correction factor for fuel mass split up in OPP_MPI_3_S_1 mode SDI (1st) pulse
The temperature correction can be calculated in two different ways for the combustion modes which have
split up between MPI and DI:
1. If (NC_MFF_TEMP_WUP_HOT_SWI = 0) then we use two different temperature factors de?ned for "cold" and
"warm" conditions. Using the fading ratio de?ned from 0 to 1 we can fade between cold/warm temperature
levels
2. If (NC_MFF_TEMP_WUP_HOT_SWI = 1) then we use three different temperature factors de?ned for "cold",
"warm" and "overtemperature" conditions.

41.12.3.1.1.2.5.6.3 Temperature correction factor for fuel mass split up in OPP_MPI_3_S_2 mode SDI (3rd)
pulse
The temperature correction can be calculated in two different ways for the combustion modes which have
split up between MPI and DI:
1. If (NC_MFF_TEMP_WUP_HOT_SWI = 0) then we use two different temperature factors de?ned for "cold" and
"warm" conditions. Using the fading ratio de?ned from 0 to 1 we can fade between cold/warm temperature
levels
2. If (NC_MFF_TEMP_WUP_HOT_SWI = 1) then we use three different temperature factors de?ned for "cold",
"warm" and "overtemperature" conditions.
Using the fading ratio de?ned from 0 to 2 we can fade either between cold/warm or between warm/overtemperature
temperature levels.

41.12.3.1.1.2.5.7.7.3.2 Temperature correction factor for fuel mass split up in CH_SA_MPI_2 mode
The temperature correction can be calculated in two different ways for the combustion modes which have
split up between MPI and DI:
1. If (NC_MFF_TEMP_WUP_HOT_SWI = 0) then we use two different temperature factors de?ned for "cold" and
"warm" conditions. Using the fading ratio de?ned from 0 to 1 we can fade between cold/warm temperature
levels
2. If (NC_MFF_TEMP_WUP_HOT_SWI = 1) then we use three different temperature factors de?ned for "cold",
"warm" and "overtemperature" conditions.
Using the fading ratio de?ned from 0 to 2 we can fade either between cold/warm or between warm/overtemperature
temperature levels.

41.12.3.1.1.2.5.7.7.5.2 Temperature correction factor for fuel mass split up in CH_SA_MPI_3_S_1 mode SDI (3rd)
pulse
The temperature correction can be calculated in two different ways for the combustion modes which have
split up between MPI and DI:
1. If (NC_MFF_TEMP_WUP_HOT_SWI = 0) then we use two different temperature factors de?ned for "cold" and
"warm" conditions. Using the fading ratio de?ned from 0 to 1 we can fade between cold/warm temperature
levels
2. If (NC_MFF_TEMP_WUP_HOT_SWI = 1) then we use three different temperature factors de?ned for "cold",
"warm" and "overtemperature" conditions.
Using the fading ratio de?ned from 0 to 2 we can fade either between cold/warm or between warm/overtemperature
temperature levels.

� General Information
The fuel mass for homogeneous injection mode is split up by the split up factor FAC_MPL_IN_HOM [NC_NR_
MFF_PLS]. Element n of FAC_MPL_INJ_HOM delivers the split up factor for injection pulse n. NC_NR_MFF_PLS
gives the maximal number of injection pulses per working cycle.
Via LC_FMSP_MPI_HPDI_MOD_ENA an additional split-up correction from the lambda adaption is considered.

Pattern for allocation of physical cylinders to exhaust bank
� General Information
The module calculates cylinder individual injections setpoints for homogeneous mode at multiple injection.
For test purposes it is possible to apply manual given values to FAC_MFF_HOM_SP.
For a global value for all cylinders this is activated with switch LC_FAC_MFF_HOM_SP_CMN_MAN.
Value is set with C_FAC_MFF_HOM_SP_CMN_MAN.
For a cylinder individual value this is activated with switch LC_FAC_MFF_HOM_SP_CYL_MAN.
Values are set with C_FAC_MFF_SP_HOM_CYL_MAN [NC_CYL_NR].
The index "i" indicates that the variable is allocated to the pattern NC_LAMB_REF.
The index "m" indicates that the variable is allocated to the pattern NC_IN_REF.
The index "x" indicates the logical cylinder.The index "n" indicates the injection pulse.
The pattern NC_LAMB_REF indicates if a logical cylinder [x] is allocated to exhaust bank 1 (i = 1, bit [x] of NC_
LAMB_REF = 0) or to exhaust bank 2 ( i = 2, bit [x] of NC_LAMB_REF = 1).
The pattern NC_IN_REF indicates if a logical cylinder [x] is allocated to intake bank 1 (m = 1, bit [x] of NC_IN_REF
= 0) or to intake bank 2 ( m = 2, bit [x] of NC_IN_REF = 1).
(The values of NC_LAMB_REF and NC_IN_REF are project speci?c.)

FMSP, Start injection fuel mass
There are two different types of starts (low pressure start and high pressure start) and combustion mode
manager (CBMD) aggregate de?nes via non calibratable variables the available start modes including also the
automatic stop-start modes.
Based on the information send by CBMD to fuel mass setpoint via current combustion mode (IDX_CMB_MOD_
CUR) a speci?c calculation of the basic fuel mass can be selected.
Basic injection fuel mass at start is determined by maps dependent on engine speed and coolant temperature
multiplied by a deactivation factor determined by maps dependent on CYC_ST and TCO in order to avoid
engine ?ooding. The deactivation factor is used to fade out the calculation of the basic injection.
Afterwards a correction factor is calculated.
For start with low fuel pressure it is determined by maps dependent on FAC_LAM_AD_OUT, (FUP_RNG_H and
TCO_ST) and (AMP and MAP_MES).
For start with high fuel pressure it is determined by maps dependent on FAC_LAM_AD_OUT and (AMP and
MAP_MES).

41.15.2.4 Calculation of MFF_CST

FMSP, Fuel quality adaptation at engine start
The purpose of fuel quality adaptation is to make sure that the engine runs without any dependency on fuel
quality. This aim is realized by an increasing or a decreasing of the injection time by a factor. For that the fuel
quality is recognized by the engine speed gradient at start.
The whole function is based on the analysis of the increase of the engine speed during the start. If a too
low engine speed gradient at start is detected the adaptation factor for the start fuel injection time will be
increased. Engine speed gradients being too high are leading to a decrease of the adaptation factor.
The ?rst decision is done with the temperature range selection (1.8: the TCO range in?uence the value of the
FQA-factor). The FQA starts after de?nite number of combustion cycles and ends due some extern impacts
(see 1.4; 1.5;1.3;1.2). With the bit LV_FQ_ST_AD (1.1) the FQA is active.
The analysis of the engine speed is done in chapter 1.7. The result set or reset the ?ags LV_FQ_ST_AD_INC/DEC_
FAC. This ?ags and the temperature decision de?nes the factor for the different temperature ranges (1.9).
The ?nal factor calculation (FAC_FQ_ST_AD) is done in chapter 1.11 (via DELTA_FAC_FQ_ST_AD and the temper-
ature range selection ).
Remark: The C_INC_... constants have to be set to positive values and
the C_DEC_... constants have to be set to negative values!

41.16.1 Activation and deactivation of the fuel quality adaptation at engine start
� General Information
The bit LV_FQ_ST_AD activates fuel quality adaptation. Some parts of the fuel quality adaptation; the temper-
ature range selection and the adaptation factor output; must be activated earlier because they are necessary
for the calculation of the ?rst start injection. The counter CTR_FQ_ST_AD_END retards the end of the fuel
quality adaptation function in order to wait for the plausibility of the FTL CAN signal. The activation of the
FQA-function depends on a de?nite number of combustion cycles.
The adaptation values are stored if the whole function ended without any error. In the case, that the fuel tank
level changed between two engine stops, the saved adaptation factors will be weighted by FAC_FQ_ST_AD_
FTL. The stored adaptation factors are initialized to 1 for after the ECU is brand new. If a relevant error occurs
in the DC, after the values in the NVMY are updated, then the adaption values of the last driving cycle should
be reused and the calculated adaption values of the actual DC should be overwritten.

41.16.2 End of adaptation
� General Information
The adaptation is activated for a certain number of combustion cycles (see 1.6: CYC_FQ_ST_AD starts running
if LV_FQ_ST_AD 0->1; calculation of LV_FQ_ST_AD see 1.1). If the cycle counter is bigger than the cycle counter
threshold for adaptation end, the adaptation is stopped. The cycle counter starts with the value 1. The adapta-
tion is stopped too, in the case when the engine speed overshoot a certain threshold beyond the idle speed
setpoint N_SP_IS, due to a very good fuel.
The fuel quality adaptation function ends later (see. LV_FQ_ST_AD_END_1) because the adaptation values still
have to be saved in the NVMY.

41.16.7 Analysis of the engine speed increase
� General Information
An upper and a lower limit give the intended engine speed increase. A map corrected by the ambient air
pressure determines each limit. These maps are dependent on the previous engine speed and the coolant
temperature. The selection of interpolation tables of minimum/ maximum engine speed difference is depend-
ing on transmission variant (MT and CVT gearbox use the MT maps, AT gearbox uses the AT maps).
Each time the real engine speed increase is outside these limits this event is counted either by the upper
limit counter CTR_N_DELTA_MAX_FQ_ST_AD or by the lower limit counter CTR_N_DELTA_MIN_FQ_ST_AD. If an
adaptation took place, the function wait a certain number of TDC�s, determined by C_CYC_UPD_DLY_FQ_ST_
AD, until a new evaluation can take place. This is due to the effect, that a new adapted fuel amount has to be
aspirated, compressed and burned before it can be evaluated. The decision to in- or decrease the adaptation
factor is made dependent on the counter maxima. After that the counter is reset. If CTR_FQ_ST_INC reaches
a calibrated threshold of increment steps in the same driving cycle (for example at re?lling with another fuel
quality) then the decrement is inhibited.

� General Information

classi?ed into one of the three temperature ranges and if it is smaller than the max. coolant temperature for
after start injection correction, the bit LV_FQ_ST_AD_AST is set to 1.

41.16.11 Correction factors for not active temperature range and adaptation factors
� General Information
If the function has once detected that an in- or decrease of the adaptation value for a speci?c temperature
range (see chapter 1.9) is necessary, then an in- or decrease of the adaptation values for the other temperature
ranges will also be necessary but with a different in-/decrement step. To handle this the actual in-/decrement
step is added to the adaptation value with different weighting factors.
As long as LV_FQ_ST_AD = 0 the adaptation factors for the different temperature ranges FAC_FQ_ST_AD_RNG_x
are equal to the saved adaptation factors FAC_FQ_ST_AD_SAVE_RNG_x.
If the adaptation is active (LV_FQ_ST_AD = 1) then the weighted in-/decrement steps DELTA_FAC_FQ_ST_AD_
RNG_x are added to the adaptation factors. These factors are limited by the parameters C_FAC_FQ_ST_AD_
MIN_RNG_x and C_FAC_FQ_ST_AD_MAX_RNG_x.
The variables DELTA_FAC_FQ_ST_AD_RNG_x are only local variables. An initialisation of the adaptation factors
can be forced by setting the bit LC_FQ_ST_AD_INI_FAC_MAN to 1. In case a decrement was detected, the factors
of the other temperature ranges will be weighted again by the factor C_FAC_FQ_ST_AD_DEC_COR.

The variables DELTA_FAC_FQ_ST_AD_RNG_x are only local variables. An initialisation of the adaptation factors
can be forced by setting the bit LC_FQ_ST_AD_INI_FAC_MAN to 1. In case a decrement was detected, the factors
of the other temperature ranges will be weighted again by the factor C_FAC_FQ_ST_AD_DEC_COR.

� General Information
This module calculates the activation and initialization conditions for fuel quality adaptation functionality eval-
uating the relevant engine conditions and information provided by error management via FARM interface.
Main output ?ags are LV_FQ_ST_AD_NOT_VLD_EXT_A and LV_FQ_ST_AD_NOT_VLD_EXT_B.
In case LV_FQ_ST_AD_NOT_VLD_EXT_A is zero than the fuel quality adaptation at start can be performed. Oth-
erwise the fuel quality adaptation at start will be deactivated.
In case LV_FQ_ST_AD_NOT_VLD_EXT_B is active the adaption factors of fuel quality will be initialized.
The following sub-functions are de?ned:
- Calculations of fuel quality activation condition
Purpose is to calculate the fuel quality adaptation validation ?ag LV_FQ_ST_AD_NOT_VLD_EXT_A based on
pedal value, independent car heater, injection authorization calculation, coolant and intake temperature and
variable valve lift position information.
- Initialization of fuel quality adaptation factors (error handling)
Purpose is to calculate the fuel quality adaptation initialization ?ag LV_FQ_ST_AD_NOT_VLD_EXT_B based on
error management information send via FARM interface (Action_FARM_GetPermission). As the errors linked
with the fuel quality adaptation strategy were to many, two NC_FID?s were de?ned (NC_FID_FQ_ST_AD_ACT
and NC_FID_FQ_ST_AD_VLD).
- Fuel tank level for fuel quality adaptation
Purpose is to calculate the actual fuel tank level and during power latch to save it in NVMY. If the fuel tank level
was stored correctly the LV_FTL_VLD_SAVE will be activated.
The actual fuel tank level and the saved one are used to determinate if the fuel tank was re?lled since last
driving cycle. In the case, that the fuel tank level changed between two engine stops, the fuel adaptation
values which will be saved need to be weighted by FAC_FQ_ST_AD_FTL.
The fuel tank information is also used for fuel RON quality determination strategy.

41.17.3 Fuel tank level for fuel quality adaptation
� General Information
This sub-function is calculating the actual fuel tank level in order to use it for fuel quality adaptation and low
ron detection strategies.
The evaluation of actual fuel tank level is performed segment synchronous and also at 10s.
During power latch the actual value of the tank level is saved in NVMY. If the level tank was stored correctly
the LV_FTL_VLD_SAVE will be activated.
The actual fuel tank level and the saved one are used to determinate if the fuel tank was re?lled since last
driving cycle. In the case, that the fuel tank level changed between two engine stops, the fuel adaptation
values which will be saved need to be weighted by FAC_FQ_ST_AD_FTL.

41.17.3.1.5 Fuel tank level calculation at transition from ignition ON to OFF
At transition from ignition key on to off (only if the engine state START was leaved) the actual fuel tank level
is evaluated. The value saved in NVMY (FTL_SAVE_FQ_ST_AD) will be equal with last actual fuel tank level
calculated before ECU off.
The ?ag indicating that a valid save was performed (LV_FTL_VLD_SAVE) is also calculated and saved in NVMY.

� General Information
To avoid lean peaks of the air-fuel mixture and to compensate inaccuracies of the intake manifold model at
low engine speed (long segment times) and fast load jumps (high dynamics of MAP_MES), an acceleration
enrichment is done for a calibratable number of segments.

part (recurrence: segment synchronous) and part for the calculation of lambda controller stop condition (re-

41.18.2.1 Calculation of trigger conditions
If the switch LC_TPS_GRD_AE is set to 1 TPS_GRD isuse for trigger, else MAF_SP_GRD is used.
The calculation of the trigger conditions based on the actual engine working point (N_32, the altitude corrected
MAP_MES and STATE_VVL_MNG and LV_TI_REAC).
If the switch LC_TPS_GRD_AE is set to 1 TPS_GRD is used for trigger, else MAF_SP_GRD is used.
There are different maps for idle speed and the other engine states.
LC_TPS_GRD_AE=1:
If the step of TPS_AV exceeds the threshold, then the trigger condition is full?lled.
LC_TPS_GRD_AE=0:
If the step of MAF_SP exceeds the threshold, then the trigger condition is full?lled.
The old value (memory value) of the step calculation is adjustable (C_NR_BUF_TPS_AV_GRD). When the trigger
conditions is full?lled once, the function switches to the enrichment state (STATE_AE = ENR) and a time counter
starts. Within the time C_T_INH_TRIG_AE, there is no retrigger possible. A trigger condition is only possible if ID_
INH_TRIG_AE = 0 for the coresponding valve lift state (STATE_VVL_MNG).

41.18.3 Runtime Improvement
For reasons of runtime-improvement, the state machine branches into the inhibit-state STATE_AE = INH if
the engine speed exceeds the calibratable threshold C_N_32_MAX_AE. It is left again if the engine speed is
lower than C_N_32_MAX_AE ? C_N_32_MAX_AE_HYS. Also for a adjustable time after start the AE functionality is
switched off. If the pressure quotient at throttle (PQ) exceeds the calibratable threshold IP_PQ_MAX_AE, then
the INH state is requested. It is left again if the PQ is lower than IP_PQ_MAX_AE ? C_PQ_MAX_AE_HYS.
STATE_AE = INH is calculated every 100 ms. If the INH state is detected, then the calculation of trigger con-
ditions is switched off directly (LV_TRIG_AE = 0 and LV_ENR_STATE_AE = 0). The calculation of enrichement
factor and lambda stop conditions will be switched off when this functionalities are expired.

41.18.4.1 Acceleration enrichement
The enrichment function is carried out in STATE_AE = ENR. When the trigger condition is active, a segment
counter is started. After a adjustable number of segments the enrichement factor is initialized with IP_MFF_
FAC_AE_INI or IP_MFF_FAC_AE_INI_VVL. The enrichement is decremented by IP_FAC_DEC_MFF_FAC_AE or IP_
FAC_DEC_MFF_FAC_AE_VVL (f(segment counter, TCO and STATE_VVL_MNG). Within a running enrichement
a new initialization is possible, if the trigger conditions are full?lled again. In this case the segment counters
start again and the initialization value of enrichement factor is set to IP_MFF_FAC_AE_INI or IP_MFF_FAC_AE_INI
_VVL.

41.19.2.3 Calculation of the split up and vaporization factors
The split up factors FAC_MFF_WF_MPI/HPDI are used to determine which fuel amount is added in the different
MPI and HPDI wall ?lm models. The number of wall ?lm model can be set by NC_NR_IM_WF_FIL and NC_NR_
CMBC_WF_FIL. The sum of all factors for MPI and the sum of all factors for HPDI must not be bigger than
1 because this will lead to a static fuel amount increase. The split up can be calibrated combustion mode
individual.
The vaporization factors are corrections of the standard vaporization dependent on temperatures and engine
operating point. The standard vaporization behavior calculated later on.

� General Information
During PUC, the manifold wall-?lm becomes cut down until it has completely disappeared.

In order to guaran-
tee, after a cylinder shut-off, safe ?ring with fast torque build-up without mis?ring of the reactivation cylinder,
this must be supplied with an extra amount of fuel for the following reasons:
- increased charge due to lack of residual exhaust gas
- wall-?lm degradation during cylinder shut-off
Because of the different numbers of cut off cycles for the cylinders, the extra fuel amount is calculated individ-
ually for each cylinder.

41.21.2.1 Intercept function : (LV_INF)
General information:
In the engine operating states trailing throttle (LV_PU) or trailing throttle fuel cut off (LV_PUC), the intercept
function (LV_INF) can be enabled below an engine speed threshold C_N_DIF_MIN_INF.
For this purpose, the engine speed gradient N_GRD is monitored.
If the negative engine speed gradient exceeds the adjustable constant IP_N_GRD_MIN during trailing throttle
fuel cut off the injection will be reactivated to counteract the high negative engine speed gradient.

41.21.2.4 Calculation of reactivation factors
General information:
In order to rebuild the previously removed wall-applied fuel ?lm during fuel cut off (LV_PUC), the injection time
is increased by this speci?c function after the injection is reactivated. This is necessary to ensure a de?ned
reactivation of the combustion after fuel cut off and to improve driveability.
Additive extra fuel quantity: At reactivation of a cylinder the extra fuel quantity is composed from the current
basic fuel mass MFF_BAS multiplied with IP_FAC_MFF_TCO_POS_WF, shortened by the cylinder individual re-
maining wall-?lm and multiplied with another factor dependant from manifold pressure MAP. In the subsequent
course this extra fuel quantity is reduced by decrementing it till 0.
Multiplicative extra fuel quantity: At reactivation of a cylinder the counter CYCNR_REAC starts with 1 and will
be incremented after every (main-) injection once per working cycle. The extra fuel amount is realised by the
table value FAC_TI_REAC. Moreover, this factor depends on the type of reactivation.
The bit?eld STATE_TI_REAC gives information about the cylinders for which the reactivation is still in progress.
If the bit at position x inside STATE_TI_REAC is equal to 1, the reactivation is in progress else not.
LC_FAC_TI_REAC_MOD_SEL= 0:
Only the bit LV_TI_REAC_MOD gives information if a "hard REAC" or "soft REAC" takes place. A change from
"soft REAC" to "hard REAC" which means from IP_FAC_TI_RIS to IP_FAC_TI_RPL is possible. Once the status "hard
REAC" is set, it is kept until the reactivation cycles of all cylinders have been ?nished (STATE_TI_REAC = 0). LV_
TI_REAC_MOD will be 0 at next injection shut of LF_INJ_INH[NC_NR_BYTE_INJ] (bitposition x) transition from
0->1).
LC_FAC_TI_REAC_MOD_SEL= 1:
Hard or soft reactivation can be selected as a function of the engine state (idle speed or part load). At reacti-
vation fuel feed cut off in idle speed, FAC_TI_RIS is used while at reactivation in part load FAC_TI_RPL is used. A
change from "soft REAC" to "hard REAC" and back is possible.

41.21.2.4.1.1.2.1.1 Calculation of multiplicative reactivation factors
The calculation of FAC_TI_RIS / RPL / REAC and MFF_ADD_REAC_CYL is done exactly like in chapter "Calculation
when injection of cylinder[x] was cut off and will now be released (LF_INJ_INH[NC_NR_BYTE_INJ] (bitposition x)
transition 1 to 0)" only CTRNR_REAC is constant 1 and will not be incremented. To improve the spec overview
it is only mentioned but not shown again graphically here. The correction factors have no in?uence to the
combustion because injection is still shut off.

41.21.2.4.1.1.3.1.1.3 Calculation of the multiplicative reactivation factors
CYCNR_REAC is incremented only after every working cycle (each 720 CRK). IP_FAC_TI_REAC_COR is a cor-
rection concerning engine speed and engine load to consider load changes during and after reactivation.
IP_FAC_TI_REAC_T_PUC is a correction depending on the time in fuel cut off by that a cool down of the com-
bustion chamber can be taken into account. IP_FAC_TI_REAC_LAM_AD_WUP_RIS / RPL is a correction factor
considering the cold adaption value FAC_LAM_AD_WUP to improve reactivation depending on fuel quality
during warm up phase.

41.21.2.4.1.1.4 Calculation when injection of cylinder[x] was released and s still released (LF_INJ_INH[NC_
NR_BYTE_INJ] (bitposition x) n-1=0 and n=0)
When the injection of cylinder[x] was release in the previous calculation and is still released now then it is
checked if the bit[x] of STATE_TI_REAC is set. In that case the calculation for soft or hard reactivation is done
and CYCNR_REAC is incremented. If MFF_ADD_REAC_CYL[x] = 0 and FAC_TI_REAC[x] = 1 or when at least 254
working cycles are gone then bit [x] of STATE_TI_REAC[x] is set to 0, FAC_TI_REAC[x] = 1, MFF_ADD_REAC_
CYL[x] = 0 (the reactivation has been ?nished)

Figure 41.21.62:
41.21.2.4.3.1.2.1.1 Calculation of FAC_TI_REAC for hard and soft reactivation
With LC_FAC_TI_REAC_MOD_SEL = 0, hard or soft reactivation is selected dependent on throttle gradient. With
LC_FAC_TI_REAC_MOD_SEL = 1, hard or soft reactivation is selected as a function of the engine state (idle speed
or part load). At reactivation fuel feed cut off in idle speed, FAC_TI_RIS is used while at reactivation in part
load FAC_TI_RPL is used. IP_FAC_TI_REAC_COR is a correction concerning engine speed and engine load to
consider load changes after reactivation. IP_FAC_TI_REAC_T_PUC is a correction depending on the time in fuel
cut off by that a cool down of the combustion chamber can be taken into account. IP_FAC_TI_REAC_LAM_
AD_WUP_RIS / RPL is a correction factor considering the cold adaption value FAC_LAM_AD_WUP to improve
reactivation depending on fuel quality during warm up phase.

Inhibition ?ag for calculation of operating point correction for the injected fuel mass at start.
� General Information
This module provides an intake bank selective correction factor MFF_COR of the injected fuel mass depending
on the actual operating point (load, engine speed). This correction accounts for bank speci?c differences of
the air charge. If the vehicle supports alternative fuel e.g. E85 (NC_AFU_CONF = 1) the interpolating tables are
doubled i.e. two sets of tables are supplied for gasoline and alternative fuel operation, respectively. The actual
correction factor depends on the alternative fuel content FAC_AFU_RATIO. Interpolation between gasoline and
?ex fuel operation is performed by the transfer function IP_FAC_AFU_RATIO_MFF_COR since fuel properties
cannot be linear interpolated.
Furthermore an cylinder individual correction is supplied account for minimum fuel mass adaptation. This
correction is set to 0 within this version.
� Application Conditions

41.23.2.1 Calculation of STST cylinder individual factor
41.23.2.1.1 Calculation of FAC_CYL_MFF_COR_STST
FAC_CYL_MFF_COR_STST[NC_CYL_NR] provides a cylinder individual correction of the injection fuel mass dur-
ing start in case of automatic stop-start. It accounts for the reduced air charge for an engine start after a
stop-start cycle compared to a normal start i.e. the correction factor is given by ratio of the actual air charge
to the air charge for a normal start. The actual charge of a cylinder depends on its individual stop position.
Directly after engine stop the cylinder charge depends on the manifold air pressure at engine stop. After a a
short time the cylinder pressure balances and is is given by the ambient pressure. The pressure balancing is
modeled by a PT1-?lter. The bit mask LF_FAC_MFF_COR assigns the cylinders for which a correction factor is a
applied(?i? denotes the index of the actual cylinder).

� General Information
This function calculates the external multiplicative fuel mass correction factors for after-start phase.
The main correction factors are calculated for cold post start (FAC_ADD_MFF_CAST_CUS), warm up (FAC_MFF_
WUP_CUS) and normal engine temperature (FAC_MFF_BAS_CUS) conditions:
1. The cold post start correction factor is dependent on coolant temperature and is speci?c for different
multipulse modes de?ned in the combustion manager. Depending on CYC_CAST_COR the cold post
start correction is faded out.

The cold post start correction factor is dependent on coolant temperature and is speci?c for different
multipulse modes de?ned in the combustion manager. Depending on CYC_CAST_COR the cold post
start correction is faded out. This correction is used for a short period after start in order to compensate
the low engine temperature.
2. In order to optimized the emissions until engine reach the optimum running temperature, the warm up
correction is used. The correction is dependent on engine speed, engine load and coolant tempera-
ture. A speci?c calculation is used for different multipulse modes de?ned in the combustion manager.
3. The correction for normal engine temperature conditions (e.g. above 60�C) is calculated based on en-
gine speed and engine load map which is factorized with a coolant temperature at start and time after
start map.

41.24.2.1.3 Warm up correction factor calculation
In order to optimize the emissions the warm up factor, which is very dependent on engine speed / engine
load, is calculated based on TCO_ST / N map and TCO_ST / MAF map, for 4 injection modes (MPLH).
This decoupling of engine speed / engine load allow the function to be calibrated on individual areas, e.g 20�C,
-7�C test, without taking in?uence on the other temperatures.
The base maps are factorized with TCO_ST / MAF_INT_AST_DC map , for 4 injection modes (MPLH)
which allow to reduce / deactivate the base maps with increasing MAF_INT_AST_DC.

FMSP, MFF Split up for multiple injection at start
� General Information
This modules calculates the split up factor FAC_MFF_MPL_INJ_ST[NC_NR_MFF_PLS] for multiple injection at
engine start. The multiple injection is used in order to improve the emissions during start phases.
The combustion mode manager (CBMD) aggregate de?nes via non calibratable variables the available start
modes for the two types of starts (low pressure and high pressure) including also the automatic stop-start
modes.
For each combustion mode a prede?ned number of injection pulses is given. Based on the information send
by CBMD to fuel mass setpoint via current combustion mode (IDX_CMB_MOD_CUR) a speci?c calculation of
split up factor can be selected.
Beside the combustion mode the main dependencies of the split up factor calculation are engine speed and
coolant temperature.
With the current system up to 4 injection pulses are possible: 1 MPI and up to 3 SDI

FMSP, Fuel mass setpoint (gen)
41.28 Fuel mass setpoint (gen)
� General Information:
This module provides calibration hints for core modules of fuel mass setpoint aggregate, so called ?Basic
Modules? (see Architecture Overview Picture from FMSP general).
� Calibration Interfering Functions
- Intake manifold model (the air path has to be calibrated to ensure the corresponding fuel mass)
- Torque set point (torque set point is input at any functions)
- Lambda Control (lambda control in?uences the fuel mass ?ow with corrections)
� Calibration Flowchart:
Figure 41.28.1:
� Calibration Process:
� Basic injection
After the end of engine start the chosen fuel mass MFF_BAS is MAF based and calculated from the torque
model. The calibration includes the combustion mode, the stoichiometric factor, the alternative fuel ratio and
the recurrence. For non intake VVL systems the former calculated MFF_BAS is mapped to the cylinder bank
speci?c values MFF_BAS_CBK_IN. For VVL systems the bank speci?c VVL position has to be considered.

FMSP, Fuel mass setpoint (gen)
For the two combustion modes (MPI, HDPI) two different MAF�s are calculated due to the different injection
phasing and the corresponding map pressure.
For the HPDI mode it is necessary if the calculation is used for the prediction of the new injection or for the
update of an already injected fuel amount (update pulse). By the map ID_MAF_MPI_SWI_CMB_MOD it can be
decided for which combustion modes this feature is used. Additionally the activation condition in the map ID_
MAF_MPI_SWI has to be tuned to 1 if the half segment counter is used (see chapter 3: run time optimization).
The map IP_MFF_FAC_AFU considers the fuel ratio of alternative fuel and the stoichiometric factor of the fuel
as well. The sampling points of the abscissa (alternative fuel ratio) should be tuned from 0 to 100%.
The map has to be tuned with the corresponding reciprocal value of the stoichiometric factor dependent on
the, e.g. for ethanol:
0% ethanol = 100% gasoline; stoichiometric factor = 14,7 (1/14,7 = 0,0680)
100% ethanol = 0% gasoline; stoichiometric factor = 13,3 (1/13,3 = 0,0752)
The sample points between could be tuned linear because the failure considering the real function
(f(x) = 1/x) is insigni?cant.
� Fuel mass set point for homogeneous mode
MFF_SP_HOM_ENG is calculated out of the basic fuel mass corresponding to the actual mass air ?ow taking in
account also the inputs from the lambda sensor, the cold post start and warm up corrections, and an external
adjustment factor.
� MFF split up for multiple injection at homogeneous mode
The calculation of split up factors is always done in same form. Basic values are de?ned in map IP_FAC_[cmb_
mod]_[number of pulse].
The pulse with the highest number (latest pulse) is calculated ?rst then the previous pulses.
The contingent between the pulses has to be determinate only for the following pulses. The ?rst pulse is
always calculated: ?rst pulse = 1 ? next pulses.
For warm up (WUP) conditions it is possible to adjust split up factors depending on TCO.
Values are calibrated with IP_FAC_[cmb_mod]_[number of pulse]_WUP and fading dependent on TCO is done
with IP_RATIO_[cmb_mod]_WUP.
Important:
Maps have to be calibrated in a way that sum of all factors = 1 (including the ?rst pulse)
Another calculation is done to avoid reaching of TI_MIN.
The ACTION_INJR_ClcTiMin4 is called, this delivers TI_MIN of actual pulse.
To this value offset C_TI_MIN_HPDI_OFS is added. Together with C_TI_STND_SDI and FAC_FUP_RATIO_STND
an inverse behavior of injector characteristic is calculated and delivers, divided with MFF_SP_HOM_MV, the
minimum split up factor to avoid TI_MIN.
This value is shown as FAC_MFF_MIN_HPDI [NC_NR_IV_PLS].
If this value is greater than calibrated value, split up factor is increased up to calibrated limitation IP_FAC_[cmb_
mod]_[number of pulse]_MAX.
For test purposes it is possible to apply manual given values to C_FAC_MFF_MPL_INJ_HOM_MAN. The activation
switch is LC_FAC_MFF_MPL_INJ_HOM_MAN_ACT.
� Calculation of fuel mass set point
MFF_SP_EFP_CTL and MFF_SP_MV are set to MFF_SP_HOM_MV. MFF_SP_EFP_CTL is used for the low pressure
electrical fuel pump control functionality.
MFF_SP_FUP_CTL is input for the high pressure fuel pressure (FUP) control functionality. This variable accounts
for the actual injection ef?ciency EFF_INJ_AV which considers cylinder shut-off. It is used for the balancing of
the fuel mass in the rail.
MFF_SP_FUP_SP is used for the fuel pressure set point FUP_SP calculation without considering cylinder shut-
off.

MFF_SP_FUP_CTL is input for the high pressure fuel pressure (FUP) control functionality. This variable accounts
for the actual injection ef?ciency EFF_INJ_AV which considers cylinder shut-off. It is used for the balancing of
the fuel mass in the rail.
MFF_SP_FUP_SP is used for the fuel pressure set point FUP_SP calculation without considering cylinder shut-
off.

FMSP, Fuel mass setpoint (gen)
� Calculation of cylinder individual fuel mass set point for HOM
The maps IP_MFF_COR_STND[NC_CBK_EX_NR] enable the bank speci?c correction of the fuel mass set point
vs. MAF and engine speed to run the engine pre controlled at lambda = 1 at every engine operating point.
Note:
Before determination of the mapping points, the intake manifold model and the injection valve characteristic
must be tuned properly. See the item ?Characteristic line of the Injector? at chapter INJR (Injection realiza-
tion).
The tuning of IP_MFF_COR_STND[NC_CBK_EX_NR] can be performed as follows:
1. Select a set of injectors which characteristic lines are close to the mean characteristic line.
2. Bring the engine to operating temperature
3. Set the lambda setpoint to l = 1 via C_LAMB_SP_MAN and activate LC_LAMB_SP_MAN_ACT. For full load
operation rich lambda setpoints may be applied in order to protect the exhaust system.
4. Deactivate the lambda controller by setting set C_N_MIN_LAM_LSCL to Nmax (8160 rpm).
5. De?ne the break points (engine speed and MAF break point).
6. Choose an engine speed and load and measure the lambda value (from system lambda sensor or
measurement lambda sensor). Bring the lambda value to the desired set point via tuning of the mapping
points.
7. Repeat item 4. for every break point.
8. Verify the result on a different engine.
If the vehicle supports alternative fuel e.g. E85 (NC_AFU_CONF = 1) the interpolating tables are doubled i.e.
two sets of tables are supplied for gasoline and alternative fuel operation, respectively. The actual correction
factor depends on the alternative fuel content FAC_AFU_RATIO. Interpolation between gasoline and ?ex fuel
operation is performed by the transfer function IP_FAC_AFU_RATIO_MFF_COR since fuel properties cannot be
linearly interpolated.
The name of the look-up tables for alternative fuel are the names of the gasoline tables with the additional
ending AFU.
Purpose of the calibration values ID_NR_CAL_MFF_HOM_SP_UPD and ID_MFF_HOM_SP_UPD[X] is to enable
different update behavior of the fuel mass for a calibratable numbers of cylinders in dependency of the com-
bustion mode switch.
The sampling points of the abscissa of ID_NR_CAL_MFF_HOM_SP_UPD include all of the injection modes. The
output values provide the numbers of the different update strategies and there the chosen index of ID_MFF_
HOM_SP_UPD[X]. ID_MFF_HOM_SP_UPD[0] should be used always to update all of the cylinders and therefore
calibrated with ?15? as the output for the logical ?eld LF_MFF_HOM_SP_UPD.
The other ID_MFF_HOM_SP_UPD[1,2,3...] provide a cylinder individual update fuel mass in dependency of the
combustion mode. For every half segment it has to be calculated which cylinder could be updated. The bit
sum has to be put into the map.
The switch to decide between one update strategy or more is LC_NR_MFF_SP_UPD_MOD_SWI_ENA.
Another constraint of the numbers of update strategies could be realized with the calibration value C_NR_MFF_
SP_UPD_MOD_SWI and the con?guration constant NC_NR_CAL_MFF_HOM_SWI_SP_UPD.
For test purposes manual values could be implemented via LC_FAC_MFF_HOM_SP_CMN_MAN and C_FAC_
MFF_HOM_SP_CMN_MAN or LC_FAC_MFF_HOM_SP_CYL_MAN and C_FAC_MFF_HOM_SP_CYL_MAN.

41.29 Fuel mass at start/after-start (gen)
� General Information:
This module provides calibration hint for fuel mass at start and after start.
� Calibration Interfering Functions
- Throttle set point calculation at start
- Idle speed actuator opening at start
- Basic ignition angle at start
- Idle speed controller
- Start pre-injection
- Injection phasing at start
- Basic lambda set point
The most of these interfering functions have to be tuned together with the fuel mass at start and after start.
It is not possible to do a standalone calibration of the fuel mass at start without changes in the interfering
functions. The other way round changes in the calibration of the interfering functions may cause a change in
the fuel mass calibration at start

� Calibration Process:
� General information
All afterwards described tunings have to be performed with reference fuel for coolant temperature at start
TCO_ST ?0�C. For starts below 0�C winter fuel has to be used. The threshold of 0�C is just a proposal. Of
course the customer speci?c demands for the start ability concerning fuel quality at different TCO_ST have to
be considered.
In the same way the customer speci?c demands for the lambda shape at and after start or the emission
standard have to be considered.
� Start pre injection (fuel mass)
The calibration pre injection fuel mass is described in an own document "Calibration hits for function Pre
injection". In general the calibration method is comparable with the calibration of the function "Start injection
fuel mass" which is described in the next chapter.
� Start injection fuel mass
The calibration starts with the adaptation of the delivered pre calibration (*.cvx-?le) to the displacement of the
engine. The pre calibration is given for a reference displacement per cylinder. It has to be corrected by the

per cylinder
At the ?rst step after the adaptation of the pre calibration to the displacement is to determine the minimum
fuel mass (lean limit) which is necessary to have combustion. Therefore the engine has to be started at
different coolant temperatures with a variation of the calibrated fuel mass for each combustion cycle. To
analyse which cycle shows a bad combustion a measurement system has to be used which calculated
the engine speed out of the tooth time of the cranking signal. These tests have to be executed for each
displacement and also separately for a system with automatic transmission because of the different engine
speed gradient. For all these tests the conditions for the exit of the start phase to the idle speed operation
state has to be set to values to ensure a longer start phase.
The base calibration maps selection of fuel mass injection at start are depending on combustion mode.
Depending on customer requirements, several starting modes can be calibrated including stop-start.
For low pressure starts the following base maps were de?ned: (IP_MFF_ST_L_1, IP_MFF_ST_L_1_H, IP_MFF_
ST_L_1_MPI, IP_MFF_ST_L_2_MPI).
For high pressure starts the following base maps were de?ned: (IP_MFF_ST_H_1_S, IP_MFF_ST_H_2_S, IP_
MFF_ST_H_3_S, IP_MFF_ST_H_3_S_2, IP_MFF_ST_H_4_MPI_2).
First to be calibrated are the low and high pressure maps which are used to determine the fuel mass limit
of the ?rst combustion cycle after pre injection for the corresponding coolant temperature. The engine
speed dependency can be ignored for the ?rst calibration. For more stable start ability these values should
be increased by 20% to have a certain distance to the lean limit of the combustion.
The deactivation factors also depending on low pressure, high pressure and stop-start modes IP_FAC_
DEAC_MFF_* have to be calibrated equal to one for CYC_ST less than the number of cylinders NC_CYL_NR.
If a pre injection is carried out also the deactivation factor for the next NC_CYL_NR cycles should be equal
to one. As a result of this calibration all cylinder get the same fuel mass for the ?rst combustion after pre
injection. Even the factor for the next NC_CYL_NR cylinder should be constant. Therefore the table index
value should have a distance of NC_CYL_NR and the deactivation factor is equal to the fuel mass limit of
the ?rst combustion after pre injection divided by the fuel mass limit of the next combustion of the same
cylinder.
Even at very cold conditions the engine should leave the engine state "start" (ST) after a certain number
of cycles. The cycle counter CYC_ST can only achieve very high values if there is a problem with the
combustion. In this case the deactivation factor has to be decreased strongly at high cycle counter values
to avoid the ?ooding of the intake manifold.

FMSP, Fuel mass at start/after-start (gen)
In the next step the engine speed dependency has to be tuned. Due to the increasing engine speed the
manifold air pressure and also the mass air ?ow decreases. If the mass air ?ow decreases also the fuel
mass has to be reduced versus engine speed. The best way to calibrate this is to have a lambda sensor for
each cylinder. Comparing of the lambda of cylinders with the same injected fuel mass and different engine
speed the dependency can be determined.
The engine speed dependency and the deactivation factor have the same purpose to reduce the fuel mass
during the proceeding engine start. This calibration hint gives just a proposal for the calibration. It is also
possible to have a small engine speed dependency and to reduce the fuel mass cylinder individual by the
deactivation factor.
For the mass fuel ?ow change limitation two sets of tables are supplied for low and high pressure startIP_
MFF_LGRD_AST_L_PRS/ IP_MFF_LGRD_AST_H_PRS. The gradient limitation is used to avoid jumps of the
mass fuel ?ow at the transition from start to after start. It can not be tuned before the warm up and cold
post start corrections are tuned.
Due to the better atomization in case of high pressure start the start injection fuel mass is lower compared to
the low pressure start.
If the engine is started after automatic engine stop (quick start) another set of maps for the deactivation factor
is used in order to apply a leaner mixture compared to a normal start.
� Warm up correction
The fuel mass out of start is basically calculated out of the mass air ?ow. For a warmed up engine this cal-
culation is accurate enough for the pre control of the fuel mass but for a cold engine corrections are necessary
to reach the lambda set point. The injected fuel mass has to be increased because of the building up of the wall
?lm at start and after start, because of fuel condensation at the cold combustion chamber wall (the fuel goes
into the oil) and because of fuel droplets which go through the engine without taking part at the combustion.
The ?rst effect is corrected by the cold post start correction. The other effects have to be corrected with the
warm up correction. To avoid a stall of the engine after start both functions have to be tuned roughly before
the ?rst engine start even before the starts for the tests described in chapter 1.2 . Therefore the pre calibration
.cvx-export should be satisfying.
For the tuning of the warm up correction a reference engine operating point has to be selected. IP_FAC_
MFF_TCO_WUP is tuned for this reference operating point. Therefore IP_FAC_MFF_WUP is set to 1 (neutral).
The tuning can be done most easily in the climatic chamber because the reference operating point can be
adjusted more accurate and the coolant temperature at start TCO_ST_DC can be free chosen.
The tests to perform are engine start at different TCO_ST_DC with a warm up at the selected operating
point. The calibration of IP_FAC_MFF_TCO_WUP is equal to the deviation of lambda controller FAC_LAM_COR
from one. The evaluation of the lambda controller value must not be started before a certain time after
start (dependent on TCO_ST_DC) because the effect of the building up of the wall ?lm takes place during this
phase.
After the tuning of the coolant temperature dependency for the reference operating point the weighting
factor for all other operating points IP_FAC_MFF_WUP has to be tuned. Therefore starts at the same TCO_
ST_DC have to be carried out with a warm up of the engine at other operating points. Again the lambda
controller deviation delivers the information to increase or decrease the warm up correction at the different
operating point. If the calibration ranges of the map IP_FAC_MFF_WUP is reached. The complete map has to
be decreased by a factor and the map IP_FAC_MFF_TCO_WUP has to be increased by the inverse factor.
� Cold post start correction
As previously described the cold post start correction is necessary to compensate the effect of building up wall
?lm after cold start. Even the pre- and start injection fuel mass consider this effect by there calibration.

If the calibration ranges of the map IP_FAC_MFF_WUP is reached. The complete map has to
be decreased by a factor and the map IP_FAC_MFF_TCO_WUP has to be increased by the inverse factor.
� Cold post start correction
As previously described the cold post start correction is necessary to compensate the effect of building up wall
?lm after cold start. Even the pre- and start injection fuel mass consider this effect by there calibration. The
difference in the calculation after start is now that the basic fuel mass is calculated out of the determined
mass air ?ow.
The calibration starts with the initialization value of the cold post start correction IP_ADD_MFF_CAST_INI and
IP_ADD_MFF_CAST_INI_AT for automatic transmission. This value is calculated at exit start and is dependent
on the coolant temperature and intake air temperature in the intake manifold TIA_IM. Therefore its clear,
that start at different TCO and different ambient temperature are necessary to tune this maps. Basically the
fuel mass wright before exit of the start is a good point of departure for the initialization value. IP_ADD_MFF_
CAST_INI has to be tuned so that the fuel mass at the transition from start to after start does not make a big

At the last step of the calibration of the cold post start correction the behaviour during the PUC operation
can be in?uenced by the calibration constant C_FAC_DEC_CAST_PUC. The neutral calibration is zero which
means that CYC_CAST_COR increases even during PUC operation. To slow down the increase of CYC_CAST_

If the vehicle is equipped with a two step VVL systems the maps for the warm up correction and cold
post start correction are doubled. The tuning of the maps has to be performed for high and low valve lift,
respectively. The calibration procedure is the same as described above.
� Restart function
If a start break off is detected (LV_ST_ES = 1 or LV_ST_VLD = 0) no restart factor is calculated: FAC_ST_REST
= 1.
For all other cases the restart factor is calculated and if the calculated factor is equal to one the ?ag LV_REST
is rest to zero.
The restart function is divided into two parts:
1. engine off duration time (T_ES_H) available and plausible
2. engine off duration time not available or not plausible
If an engine off duration time is available both function parts have to be calibrated.
For the tuning of the function the lambda shape at restart during the engine warm up has to be mea-
sured.
Engine off duration time available:
At the ?rst step restarts after completely build up wall ?lm are considered. To ensure that the wall ?lm is
build up the engine has to run in idle until the cold post start correction is over before it is turned off for the
next start. Several warm ups have to be performed with different engine off duration time in-between.
The main map for the calculation of the restart factor is IP_REST. The neutral value for IP_REST is zero
(same fuel mass at restart as if it was a ?rst start). The fuel mass at restart has to be decreased (values below
zero) because of the already build up wall ?lm from the last engine run. After several minutes this wall ?lm
evaporates so that the restart correction becomes neutral. For the calibration the measured lambda shape
has to be compared with a ?rst start.
For restarts during wall ?lm build up (cold post start correction is active) the fuel mass would be decreased
too much. Therefore the calibration of IP_REST can be weakened by IP_FAC_REST dependent on time after
start T_AST and TCO. The neutral value for this map is one. To tune IP_FAC_REST the engine is turned off at
different time after start values to see where the privies calibration has too much impact on the lambda.
Engine off duration time not available or not plausible:
The corresponding map for IP_REST in case of no engine off duration time is the IP_FAC_STND_REST. But
this map is just used if the coolant temperature has not decreased below the coolant temperature at engine
shut down TCO_STOP minus the tunable parameter C_TCO_DIF_MAX_REST. The difference between the actual
coolant temperature TCO and the coolant temperature at engine shut down delivers the engine off duration
time to a certain extend. C_TCO_DIF_MAX_REST is equal to the decrease of TCO within an engine off duration
time where a restart correction is necessary.
The second tunable parameter C_T_AST_STOP_MAX_REST is used to avoid restart correction during the
building up of the wall ?lm. This value has to be set to maximum time after start where the cold post start
correction can be active.
In both cases the restart factor can be corrected if "engine stall" is detected. This means that the engine
stopped without the intention of the driver (ignition key not used). Thereby the injection was not cut off. This
leads to a different wall ?lm in comparison with a standard engine shut down which can be corrected with the
map IP_FAC_STALL.
� Ambient pressure correction
Due to the fact that the pre injection and the start injection fuel mass are pre controlled and not based on the
mass air ?ow both fuel masses have to be corrected dependent on the ambient pressure. Therefore engine
start tests at high altitude or in a special chamber have to be done. The pre calibration of the map IP_FAC_ST_
AMP mostly enables a good starting performance. The ?ne tuning is done based on the comparison with the
lambda shape at standard altitude.

the temperature range 4 were used for temperature range 5 too. In the temperature ranges 4, 3, 2 and 1 an
adaptation takes place and the adaptation values are saved in the NVMY. In the temperature range 0 no
adaptation takes places. The adaptation values from range 1 were used and linear ramped down towards 1.0
until C_MAX_TCO_ST_RNG_0 is reached.
In the case that the voltage battery is to low, the gas pedal is pressed or CRK error, CAM error, MAF error, MAP
error or injection valves error are detected then the FQA function will be disabled. The inhibit conditions are

41.31.1 Run time optimization
This functionality is intended to reduce the CPU load by means of reducing cylinder dependent calculations
from all cylinders to one cylinder. That means if the engine speeds is greater than the threshold C_N_32_THD_
CLC_RED not all but only one cylinder is updated with actual data at segments events. The assignment of
the cylinders to the segments is given by the map ID_CTR_CYL_NR_CLC(SEG_NR). This map has to be tuned in
such way that the logical cylinder is going to be injected right after the actual segment. Furthermore, intake
and exhaust bank dependent calculations are reduced to the bank which corresponds to the actual cylinder.
The assignments of the cylinders to intake and exhaust banks are given by the con?guration data NC_IN_REF
and NC_LAMB_REF, respectively.
If the engine speed falls below threshold and hysteresis C_N_32_HYS_CLC_RED all cylinder are calculated
again. The module should be activated only if there is a need for reduction of runtime, this means the engine
speed threshold should be not lower than necessary. A typical value for a 6 cylinder engine would be 5800
rpm.
The variable STATE_CLC_ RED supplies the calculation frequency for the intake manifold model.
The calculation frequency could be:
- every half segment (if half segment trigger is available)
- every segment
- every second segment

FMSP, Wall ?lm correction fuel mass setpoint (gen)
41.32 Wall ?lm correction fuel mass setpoint (gen)
� General Information:
The control of the air/fuel ratio is one of the most important tasks in the SI engine control system due to its
effects on the reduction of exhaust emissions with three way catalytic converters. One of the critical dynamics
for the air/fuel ration control is wall wetting phenomenon.
To compensate the build-up / removal of the fuel ?lm in the intake ducts (MPI system) and inside combustion
chamber (SDI system), the in stationary wall ?lm compensation function provides an additive positive/negative
mass fuel ?ow MFF_ADD_WF.
The wall ?lm strategy is based on a calibratable number of physical models for intake manifold (NC_NR_IM_
WF_FIL) and for combustion chamber (NC_NR_CMBC_WF_FIL).
Usually at least two physical models for each injection type (MPI, SDI) are used, a ?rst order model and parallel
model (2nd order).
The ?rst order model suggests that a portion of the fuel mass injected immediately enters the cylinders directly
while the remainder is stored in fuel puddles on the intake manifold runner wall. The quantity of fuel leaves the
walls at a rate proportional to the mass of the quantity applied to the walls. This amount gradual evaporates
during subsequent engine cycles. This assumes a single time constant for evaporation.
The 1 st order assumption of single time constant for evaporation is often not suf?cient. To improve the
1st order model structure additional parallel dynamic paths (2 nd, 3 rd ...order) can be added. The physical
interpretation is the same as the 1st order with the exception that the additional paths represents another fuel
puddle with different time constant of evaporation.
In the example below a 2 nd order model is considered (fast and slow path) with different time constants of
evaporation.

� Technical overview
The calculation of the fuel wall ?lm compensation function is based on the basic fuel mass ?ow MFF_BAS

The function is activated attransition from the engine operating state ST to PL or IS and is applied in all oper-
ating states except ES and ST. The calculation is executed every segment and also half segment trigger (e.g.
every 180 �CRK or 90 �CRK for a 4-cylinder engine).
The function can have a con?gurable number of wall ?lm models for both injection types (MPI, SDI).
Figure 41.32.3:
All de?ned paths are calculated in parallel and are almost identical. Between two sampling steps (segment
trigger) the steady state wall ?lm differential quantity is determined. This quantity is corrected depending on
the actual coolant temperature and on effects due to intake air temperature.
The compensation quantities calculated for each path are not identical due to different application data. Usu-
ally the ?rst path quantity is bigger than the following quantities but fades away much faster. Different appli-
cation data can be applied for positive and negative load changes. The total (cylinder speci?c) compensation
quantity MFF_ADD_WF_CYL_x is the sum of the fast and the slow quantity.

1.  **Lookup Table for Base Factor A**: The engine speed `<N>` (acting as the x-axis input) and predicted MAF `<MAF_STK_FG_PRED>` (acting as the y-axis input) are fed into a 2D lookup table named `IP_FAC_CH_SA_MPI_2_PLS_1`. This table outputs a base correction factor, designated as `A`.

## Function

This diagram, specifically **Figure 41.19.16**, performs the initialization of the intake manifold reference wall film. Its primary function is to calculate the steady-state amount of fuel held as a film on the intake manifold walls for each engine cylinder. ## Diagram 1: Calculation of MFF_ADD_REAC_CYL

### Function
The primary function of this diagram is to calculate an additional mass fuel flow per cylinder (`MFF_ADD_REAC_CYL`) that compensates for reactivity variations. This compensation is derived by scaling a base fuel mass flow by factors determined from engine coolant temperature (TCO) and manifold absolute pressure (MAP), and then applying a final global correction factor.

### Inputs
*   **`<MFF_BAS>`**: Base Mass Fuel Flow (likely the main, uncorrected fuel quantity).
*   **`<TCO>`**: Engine Coolant Temperature.
*   **`<MAP>`**: Manifold Absolute Pressure.
*   **`<FAC_COR_MFF_ADD_REAC_CYL>`**: A calibration-dependent correction factor for the additional reactive mass fuel flow per cylinder.

### Outputs
*   **`<MFF_ADD_REAC_CYL>`**: The calculated additional mass fuel flow for reactivity per cylinder.

### Logic Flow
1.  **Temperature-dependent Factor Calculation**: The `<TCO>` input is fed into a 1D look-up table (represented by the waveform symbol) labeled `IP_FAC_MFF_TCO_POS_WF`. This look-up table determines a multiplicative factor based on the engine coolant temperature.
2.  **Pressure-dependent Factor Calculation**: The `<MAP>` input is fed into another 1D look-up table labeled `IP_FAC_MFF_MAP_WF`. This look-up table determines a multiplicative factor based on the manifold absolute pressure.
3.  **Combined Reactivity Factor**: The two factors obtained from the `TCO`-dependent and `MAP`-dependent look-up tables are multiplied together. This creates a combined environmental factor influencing reactivity.
4.  **Base Fuel Flow Scaling**: The combined reactivity factor is then multiplied by the `<MFF_BAS>` (Base Mass Fuel Flow). This scales the base fuel flow to account for the detected reactivity influence.
5.  **Final Correction**: The scaled fuel flow value is further multiplied by the global correction factor `<FAC_COR_MFF_ADD_REAC_CYL>`.
6.  **Output Assignment**: The final result of these sequential multiplications is assigned to the output variable `<MFF_ADD_REAC_CYL>`.
    *In summary: `MFF_ADD_REAC_CYL = MFF_BAS * (IP_FAC_MFF_TCO_POS_WF(TCO) * IP_FAC_MFF_MAP_WF(MAP)) * FAC_COR_MFF_ADD_REAC_CYL`*
